column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AN ABF CITY DRIVER BACKED TO THE DOCK AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY AND CONTACTED THE RECEIVING CLERK.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE TOTE TANK, THEY FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT (<8 OZ) ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TOP OF THE TOTE TANK AROUND THE SEAL.  THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED TO ACCEPT THIS TOTE TANK UNLESS THE DRIVER TOOK A RAG AND CLEANED OFF AROUND THE TOP.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CLEAN IT OFF, BUT IN THE PROCESS, BECAME LIGHT-HEADED.  HE CALLED ABF AND SPOKE WITH THE OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR AND ADVISED HIM OF THE SITUATION.  HE ALSO ADDED AT THAT TIME THAT A RESPONSE TEAM MAY BE AVAILABLE LATER THAT DAY.  THE OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO RETURN TO THE TERMINAL WITH THE TANK.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TERMINAL, THE DRIVER WAS ALSO HAVING BREATHING PROBLEMS.  THE SAFETY & SECURITY DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE CLINIC AS A SAFETY PRECAUTION.  THE SHIPPER PROVIDED A MSDS TO THE CLINIC.  THE CLINIC THEN WANTED THE DRIVER TO GO TO THE ALTA BATES HOSPITAL IN OAKLAND FOR FURTHER TESTING.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN AND THE TESTS RUN WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS.  THIS DRIVER IS A KNOWN ASTHMATIC. A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM THE TOWNSHIP OF PALMER LOCATED AT 3600 HARTLEY AVENUE IN PALMER, PA TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY,INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S DEPTFORD SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2301 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE IN DEPTFORD NJ. UPON ARRIVAL AT THIS LOCATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT  A PIECE OF EQUIPMENT BEING TRANSPORTED IN THE VEHICLE SHIFTED IN TRANSIT AND PUNCTURED ONE 55 GALLON CONTAINER RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO  A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  IN ADDITION, 1 x 55 GALLON CONTAINER OF CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE VAN TRAILER'S FLOOR.  THIS MATERIAL WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. ALONG WITH THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT. A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT IDENTIFIED THAT THE  BLOCKING AND BRACING DEVICE USED TO SECURE THE LOAD FAILED CAUSING THE PIECE OF EQUIPMENT TO SLID INTO THE 55 GALLON DRUM WHICH WAS DAMAGED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, ALL DRIVER AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTURED TO INSURE THAT THE BLOCKING AND BRACING DEVICES USED ARE FUNCTIONING PROPERLY AND ARE CAPABLE OF SECURING THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT.

column168: ON SATURDAY, MAY 18,1996, OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING SOUTHBOUND ON RT. 202 IN NJ AT APPROXIMATELY 45-50 MPH. OUR DRIVER WAS FINISHING MAKING A LANE CHANGE (RIGHT TO LEFT), AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF HOLLAND BROOK RD. HE SAW A DARK COLORED VAN (1990 CHEVROLET) PULL OUT INTO THE SOUTHBOUND TRAFFIC LANES WITHOUT YIELDING TO TRAFFIC. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE, A SEVEENTEEN (17) YEAR OLD FEMALE, PULLED OUT INTO THE ROADWAY LOOKING TO HER RIGHT. THERE WAS ALSO A 15 YEAR OLD FEMALE PASSENGER IN THE VAN. OUR DRIVER SOUNDED HIS AIR HORN AND STEERED TO THE LEFT IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID HITTING THE VAN. THE DRIVER OF THE VAN NEVER TURNED TO THE LEFT UP AND TO THE POINT OF IMPACT. THE VAN CONTINUED ACROSS THE INTERSECTION COLLIDING WITH THE FRONT RIGHT OF OUR TRACTOR AND HER FRONT LEFT. OUR DRIVER HAD TO STEER RIGHT JUST ABOUT AT THE POINT OF IMPACT, DUE TO ANOTHER VEHICLE WHICH WAS PREPARING TO TURN IN THE NORTHBOUND RT. 202 TURNING LANE. AFTER OUR TRACTOR COLLIDED WITH THE VAN, OUR DRIVER STATED THAT HE THEN SWERVED TO THE RIGHT, LOST SOME STEERING AND PROCEEDED TO CLIMB AN EMBARKMENT, AND FINALLY CAME TO A STOP. OUR DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO RELEASE HIS SEATBELT WHEN THE ENTIRE TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT BEGAN TO ROLLOVER TO THE LEFT ONTO THE ROADWAY. OUR DRIVER EXITED THE TRACTOR THROUGH THE PASSENGER SIDE WINDOW AND PROCEEDED TO RUN DOWN TOWARDS THE INTERSECTION. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT RT. 202 SOUTHBOUND HAS A DECLINE DOWN WHEN APPROACHING HOLLAND BROOK RD., AND AN INCLINE AFTER THE INTERSECTION. OUR DRIVER BEGAN TO WARN TRAFFIC BEHIND HIS VEHICLE TO KEEP BACK AND TO CLEAR THE LOW AREA, DUE TO SEEPAGE OF GASOLINE PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK TRAILER RUNNING DOWNHILL TOWARDS THE INTERSECTION. AT THIS TIME, OUR DRIVER SAW AN EMT (EMERGENCY MEDICAL TECHNICIAN) WHO APPARENTELY SAW THE ACCIDENT AND WENT TO HIM. WHILE WAITING FOR AN AMBULANCE, OUR DRIVER WAS SITTING ON A CURB AND SPEAKING WITH THE TWO OCCUPANTS (GIRLS) OF THE VAN. ONE OF THE GIRLS (THE DRIVER) WAS CRYING AND APOLOGIZING TO OUR DRIVER FOR WHAT SHE HAD DONE. OUR DRIVER ALONG WITH TWO FEMALES FROM THE CHEVROLET VAN WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE SOMERSET MEDICAL CENTER, IN SOMERVILLE, NJ FOR TREATMENT OF INJURIES. OUR DRIVER SUSTAINED MINOR INJURIES TO HIS HEAD, CHEST AND ABDOMEN. THE INJURIES TO THE TWO FEMALES IS NOT KNOWN AT THIS TIME. OUR DRIVER INFORMED US THAT THE OCCUPANTS OF THE VAN WERE SHAKEN UP, BUT NOT SEVERELY INJURED. OUR DRIVER WAS RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL THE DAY OF THE ACCIDENT. LOCAL POLICE, FIRE DEPARTMENTS, AND HAZ-MAT SPILL RESPONSE TEAMS WERE SUMMONDED TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. RT. 202 WAS SHUTDOWN IN BOTH DIRECTIONS TO ALL TRAFFIC. HAZ-MAT OPERATIONS WERE INITIATED AND PRODUCT TRANSFER FROM THE OVERTURNED TANKER TO A STANDBY TRAILER WERE CONDUCTED. AFTER THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETE, THE OVERTURNED TRACTOR TRAILER WAS UP-RIGHTED, AND TOWED AWAY. CLEANUP AND RECOVERY OPERATIONS WERE INITIATED WITHIN ONE HOUR OF INCIDENT AND CONTINUED THROUGHOUT THE DAY. OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, A BOX FELL OFF THE PALLET AND LANDED UPSIDE DOWN. THIS CAUSED ONE BOTTLE TO CRACK OPEN. THE HAZMAT RELEASE WAS VERY SMALL. DOCKWORKERS NEED TO TAKE MORE CARE WHEN MOVING HAZMAT SHIPMENTS.

column168: CARTON HAD BEEN LOOSE ON TOP OF PALLET OF FREIGHT AT THE ORIGIN TERMINAL. DURING TRANSIT THE CARTON BECAME WEDGED BEHIND THE PALLET OF FREIGHT THAT IT HAD BEEN LOADED ON.  THE DOCK MAN AT THE NEXT FREIGHT UNLOADING FACILITY STARTED TO UNLOAD THE PALLET.  AS HE PULLED THE PALLET BACK THE WEDGED CARTON FELL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR ON ITS SIDE.  THE IMPACT CAUSED THE LIDS OF THE CANS INSIDE THE CARTON TO POP LOOSE.  THE DOCK MAN PICKED UP THE CARTON AND WHEN HE DID SOME OF THE CORROSIVE LIQUID SPILLED ON HIS LEG.  HE WENT TO A TREATMENT FACILITY WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PUT IN OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  THE FREIGHT LOADER AT THE ORIGIN TERMINAL SHOULD NOT HAVE LOADED THE CARTON LOOSE ON TOP OF A PALLET OF FREIGHT.  THE CARTON SHOULD HAVE BEEN LOADED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.

THE FREIGHT LOADER AT ORIGIN SHOULD NOT HAVE PLACED THE HEAVY CARTONS  ON TOP OF THE DRUM WITHOUT THE BENEFIT OF A PALLET BETWEEN THE DRUM TOP AND THE CARTONS.

column168: ODORS WERE DETECTED IN VICINITY OF CAR.  YARD AND MAIN LINE WERE TEMPORARILY CLOSED UNTIL ATSF RESPONDER ASSESSED CAR.  PRODUCT WAS VENTED FROM CAR ACCOUNT THE CAR WAS PRESUMED TO BE OVER FILLED.  SAFETY VALVE RESEATED AND CAR WAS HELD FOR OBSERVATION AND FURTHER REDUCTION OF TWO TANK TRUCKS LOADS OF PRODUCT (BY SHIPPER).  CAR WAS AGAIN REPORTED TO BE VENTING 5/15 AT 730 PT.  AS SAFETY VALVE WAS PRESUMED TO BE DEFECTIVE, PLANS WERE EXECUTED TO OFF LOAD CAR AND DISPATCH CAR TO REPAIR SHIP.  YARD OPERATIONS WRE SUSPENDED FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR FOR ASSESSMENT.  AS VENTING HAD STOPPED AND WIND WAS STRONG THIS WAS CONSIDERED ACCEPTABLE.

THORUGH FREIGHT TRAIN CREW OBSERVED TANK CAR VENTING AND SET CAR OUT OF THEIR TRAIN.  ICING WAS ALSO NOTED.  ATSF RESPONDER ASSESSED CRYOGENIC CAR AND CHECKED INTERNAL COMODITY PRESSURE (WHICH WAS 28 PSI).  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND SUGGESTED VENTING THE CAR TO REDUCE PRESSURE TO 15 PSI. COMODITY WAS VENTED THROUGH THE VAPOR LINES.  THIS STABILIZED THE CARS VENTING THROUGH THE RELIEF VALVE.  A FINAL PRESSURE OF 18 PSI WAS OBTAINED.  THE CAR WAS RELASED TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

TANK CAR SPLASHED PRODUCT OUT OF SAFETY VENT DURING SWITCHING SWITCH FORMAN WAS SPLASHED WITH PRODUCT ON HIS ARMS.  ATSF RESPONSE ASSESSED CAR AND FOUND FAILED FRANGIBLE DISK.  DISK WAS REPLACED, AND CAR AND GROUND WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH THROUGH ASSISTANCE FROM THE BAKERSFIELD FIRE DEPARTMENT  EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY SHOWERED TO DILUTE PRODUCT. HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED WITHOUT RESTRICTIONS BY A DOCTOR.  CAR WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

SABRETECH CORPORATION, AN FAA-APPROVED AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE FACILITY AT MIAMI AIRPORT, OFFERED 5 CARDBOARD BOXES CONTAINING OXYGEN GENERATORS TO CARGO LOADERS OF VALUJET FLIGHT 592, SCHEDULED TO DEPART FOR ATLANTA AT 2PM ON MAY 11. WE NOW UNDERSTAND THAT THESE GENERATORS HAD NOT BEEN DISCHARGED, NOR WERE THEY EQUIPPED WITH SAFETY CAPS OR OTHERWISE PACKED TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL DISCHARGE UNDER NORMAL CONDITIONS OF TRANSPORTATION. THE SEALED BOXES WERE OFFERED FOR AIR SHIPMENT ON A SABRETECH SHIPPING TICKET CONSIGNING THEM TO VALUJET'S FACILITY IN ATLANTA. THE SHIPPING TICKET MISDESCRIBED THE CONTENTS AS "OXY CANNISTERS EMPTY" AND INCLUDED NO INFORMATION ON THE CLASS, PROPER SHIPPING NAME, OR UN IDENTIFICATION NUMBER FOR THIS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. IT DID NOT INDICATE THE SHIPMENT WAS AUTHORIZED FOR PASSANGER AIRCRAFT, NOR WAS IT CERTIFIED. IT ALSO DID NOT IDENTIFY THE SHIPMENT AS HAZARDOUS WASTE UNDER RCRA. NO BOXES BORE UN PERFORMANCE STANDARD MARKINGS, OR MARKING OF THE SHIPPING NAME OR UN IDENTIFICATION NUMBER OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. NO "OXIDIZER 5.1" LABELS WERE AFFIXED. SABRETECH GAVE VALUJET'S PERSONNEL NO INFORMATION TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE NTSB'S INVESTIGATION HAS IMPLICATED SABRETECH'S SHIPMENT IN THE CRASH OF FLIGHT

column168: DURING SAFETY CHECK, DRIVER FOUND THAT ONE DRUM INSIDE THE TRAILER HAD BEGUN TO LEAK.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND CONTAINED.  ALL WASTE PRODUCT WAS THEN DELIVERED TO THE RECEIVER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOON HIGHWAY 77 WHEN A NORTH BOUND PASSENGER CAR CROSSED OVER THE CENTER LINE COLLIDING WITH THE FRONT AND TEARING THE FRONT AXLE OUT OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE MAKING IT UNSTEARABLE. THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE CONTINUED SO AND THE READ WHEELS TRAVELED OVER THE CARS FRONT.  THIS TORE THE TRAILER TANDEMS FROM THE TRAILER, THE CAR CAME TO REST IN THE SOUTH BOUND LANE.  THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE TRAVELED INTO THE NORTH BOUND GUARD RAIL AND THEN WAS DEFLECTED INTO A ROCK BANK, THIS IGNITED THE DIESEL FUEL TANK ON THE PASSENGER SIDE AND CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO CROSS THE HIGHWAY AND DOWN AN EMBANKMENT WHERE IT CAME TO REST, DURING THIS TIME THE TRAILER TURNED ON ITS SIDE RELEASING SOME CARGO.  THE TRACTOR BURNED UP COMPLETELY.
column172: Highway hopper trailer for solid materials only

column168: DRIVER MADE SUDDEN STOP, PRODUCT CAME OUT FRONT WASH CAP ON TOP OF TRAILER.  CORDOVA POLICE AND FIRE DEPT NOTIFIED.

ON MAY 9, 1996 AT APPROXIMATELY 1500, A DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK UP THE REFERENCED CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE WHEN HE NOTICED THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING AND REPORTED IT TO HAPAG-LLOYD.  HAPAG-LLOYD IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE USCG, THE GPA (TERMINAL OPERATOR), CONSIGNEE, AND NOMINATED THE NCB AS SURVEYOR FOR HAPAG-LLOYD.  THE CONSIGNEE NOMINATED COASTAL DIVERS AS THE RESPONSE TEAM.  UNDER DIRECTION OF THE USCG, THE CONTAINER DOORS WERE OPENED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS NOTED AT THE REAR SILL.  NO PRODUCT WAS NOTED TO HAVED LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  IT WAS CLOSED AND CORDONED OFF.  AT 0800 ON MAY 10, DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  TWO DRUMS WERE FOUND TO HAVE SMALL LEAKS FROM THE TOP AND BOTTOM CHIMES.  ONE OF THEM WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE FILLING CAP WHICH WOULD INDICATE OVERFILLING. THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVER PACKS.  THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE USCG AND DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  CONSIGNEE ADVISED THAT DUE TO HISTORY OF PROBLEMS WITH THESE DRUMS, THEY ARE REVIEWING GOING TO ISO TANKS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1215 HOURS, MAY 1, 1996, A DRIVER AT THE CONRAIL TOLEDO OHIO TRAILVAN FACILITY REPORTED SEEING LIQUID PRODUCT COMING FROM CONTAINER COER 100086 AS IT WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A TRUCK CHASSIE. INCIDENT REPORTED TO FACILITY MANAGER AND APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS MADE INCLUDING CHEMTREC, OHIO EPA AND US EPA.  PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL.  SHIPPER HAD PLACED MOISTURE LADEN PRODUCT IN A SOLID ONLY CONTAINER.  MANIFEST ATTACHED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS ON MAY 5TH, IN HASELTON YARD, CREW YIHN-91 SWITCHED FOUR LOADED GONDOLAS AGAINST FLAT CAR BN 621799 CAUSING TWO CONTAINERS TO SHIFT ON THE CAR AND THE DOOR OF AAR45 TO BULGE AT THE BOTTOM WHEN THE EQUIPMENT SHIFTED INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  THIS BULGE ALLOWED A GAP OF ONE INCH TO OPEN UP AND MATERIAL TO SEEP ONTO THE CAR FLOOR.  THE CONSIGNEE AND FEDERAL AND STATE REPRESENTATIVES WERE IN ATTENDANCE.  THE CONSIGNEE CLEANED THE CAR, PLACED A CATCH BASIN UNDER THE DOOR, ADJUSTED THE CONTAINERS ON THE CAR, COVERED THE CONTAINER END WITH PLASTIC, AND THEN SECURED A STEEL PLATE AGAINST THE DOOR TO PREVENT ANY ADITIONAL RELEASE.  THE CAR WAS HANDLED IN A SPECIAL TRAIN TO THE CONSIGNEE (APPROXIMATELY 40 MILES).

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TOTE AT APPROX 19:30 5/31/96 FROM TRAILER 41601, WE NOTICED A CLEAR LIQUID SUBSTANCE ON TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  THE SUBSTANCE APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM THE LID AREA.  CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE HAZ MAT AREA AND ISOLATED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 19:45 AND AT APPR. 20:10 HRS KEN GAWRYLA FROM ATOTEC CALLED AND THE INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED.  WE WERE TOLD TO LEAVE THE TOTE IN AN ISOLATED AREA AND ATOTECH WOULD HAVE A REPRESENTATIVE COME TO THE TERMINAL ON 06-02/96 AT 0800 TO CLEAR CONTAINER AND GIVE INSTRUCTIONS ON TRANSPORTING IT.
WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, DISCOVERED A TANK LEAKING FROM A FAULTY SEAM. THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND REPAIRED THE TANK.  THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED.
WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, A CARTON WAS FOUND DAMAGED.  THE MATERIAL HAD EVAPORATED AND THE REMAINDER OF THE FREIGHT WILL BE DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.

A ROLL-OFF TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM THE PORTSMOUTH NAVAL SHIPYARD LOCATED ON SEAVY ISLAND IN KITTERY, ME TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE TIRE AND LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE SIDE WALL OF THE ROLL-OFF CAN ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA WHERE THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND NOTIFIED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE TO INITITATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER THAT WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED HAD SEPARATED OUT FROM THE SOLID PORTION OF THE SHIPMENT AND ESCAPED THROUGH A SMALL OPENING THAT HAD DEVELOPED ALONG THE SIDE WALL OF THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER.  THE CLEAN-UP CREW PATCHED THE SMALL OPENING AND SOLIDIFIED ALL FREE LIQUIDS.  ONCE THIS ACCOMPLISHED, THE TRUCK WAS ESCORTED TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY WHERE THE SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED AND PROCESSED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRANCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE DRIVER HAD BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT EACK ROLL-OFF CAN IN INSPECTED PRIOR TO ACCEPTANCE TO INSURE THAT THE STRUCTUAL INTERGRITY OF THE CONTAINER IS ACCEPTANCE TO INSURE THAT THE STRUCTURAL INTERGRITY OF THE CONTAINER IS ACCEPTABLE. IN ADDITION, ANY FREE LIQUIDS THAT ARE DISCOVERED AT THE TIME THE SHIPMENT IS ACCEPTED MUST BE ADDRESSED PRIOR TO ACCEPTING THE SHIPMENT.

column168: YARD SWITCH CREW REPORTED STENCIL WHILE SHOVING CAR INTO TRACK.  THE ENGINEER DEVELOPED HAUSEA, EYE IRRITATION AND MUCOUS MEMBRANE IRRITATION FROM INHALATION OF THE VAPOR RELEASED.  THE SWITCHED FOREMAN REPORTED TIGHTNESS IN HIS CHEST AND DID GO TO SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION.  BNSF RESPONDER ASSESSED TWO POTENTIAL CULPRIT CARS AND LOCATED SOURCE OF RELEASE TO BE THIS CAR. PACKAGING MATERIAL WAS ADDED TO FORM A SEAL UNDER THE PACKING GLAND NUT.  BOTH EMPLOYEES WERE EXAMINED AND RELEASED.

OUR DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER A LOAD OF DIESEL TO THE METROPLOTIAN TRANSIT AUTHORITY IN LOS ANGELES.  AFTER MEASURING THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK HE WAS TOLD BY THE FACILITY OPERATOR THAT THE PRODUCT TO BE DELIVERED WOULD FIT INTO THE TANK.  UPON UNLOADING THE TANK OVERFLOWED APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS.  THE DIESEL WAS SPILLED ONTO A CONCRETE SLAB AND WAS CLEANED UP WITH A MOP.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE, THE FACILITY OPERATOR SHOULD DOUBLE CHECK, AND CONFIRM WHAT WILL AND WILL NOT FIT INTO THEIR TANKS.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT THE TERMINAL WITH 3-4 CARTONS WET.  AFTER INVESTIGATING THE PROBLEM IT WAS FOUND THAT A NAIL IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER PUNCTURED ONE OF THE CARTONS.  THIS THEN ALLOWED THE PRODUCT FROM THE 1-1 GALLON JUG TO LEAK OUT ONTO THE OTHER CARTONS.  THE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED INTO THE CARDBOARD.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND WE RECEIVED RETURN AUTHORITY.  THE 3-1 GALLON CONTAINERS HAVE BEEN PLACED INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND THEN PLACED IN A 8-GALLON OVERPACK WHICH WAS MARKED AND LABELED PRIOR TO RETURN.  THE LOADING TERMINAL HAS BEEN SENT A LOAD REPORT WHICH INSTRUCTS THE DOCKMAN TO CHECK THE TRAILER PRIOR TO LOADING.  THIS SHOULD PREVENT ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

AS DRIVER UNLOADED TRUCK AT THE LOADING DOCK, HE LOST CONTROL OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER FELL FROM THE LIFTGATE OF THE VEHICLE TO THE PAVED PARKING LOT OF THE FACILITY.  UPON IMPACT, THE CONTAINER LID CAME OFF, ALLOWING CONTENTS TO BE RELEASED.  TO HELP PREVENT RECURRENCE, A BOLT-RING LID ASSEMBLY IS BEING PHASED IN.  THIS WILL PROVIDE A MORE SECURE CLOSURE.

AN FRA INSPECTOR REVIEWING OUR MORGANTOWN, WV RAIL SIDING DISCOVERED A LEAK ON A RAIL CAR AT THE GAGING DEVICE.  APPARENTLY THE PACKING GLAND FOR THIS DEVICE WAS NOT SECURE (TIGHT), AND WAS LEAKING AMMONIA VAPOR.  WE DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO THE LOCATION.  THEY TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND AND NO FURTHER LEAKS OCCURED.  SUPPLIER WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT IN ORDER TO TRY AND PREVENT ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE CAR DEPARTMENT DISCOVERED PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF TANK CAR TILX 100009.  THE DISTRICT SUPERINTENDENT INVESTIGATED AND FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC RUPTURED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND RESCAR SUMMONED. REPRESENTATIVES FROM DIAZ INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE HARD AND TWISTED THUS NOT MAKING AN APPROPRIATE SEAL. THEY USED A NEW TEFLON GASKET TO REPLACE THE DEFECTIVE GASKET. column168: THIS FIT (DRUM) CAME INTO TERMINAL ON 1 SKID, SO THE WAREHOUSEMAN USED A FORKLIFT TO UNLOAD FREIGHT.  WHILE HE WAS UNLOADING THE DRUM HE WAS TAKING IT OFF HIS TRAILER AND TAKING IT TO THE DESIGNATED TRAILER.  WHILE TRANSPORTING   THE DRUM, WITH A FORKLIFT, THE DRIVER WENT OVER A BUMP ON THE DOCK CAUSING THEDRUM TO SLIP THROUGH SOME CRACKED BOARDS ON THE PALLETS.  WHEN THIS HAPPENED  THE FORKLIFT BLADES PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TURNED THE DRUMON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. HE APPLIED DUST DOWN TO CLEAN THESMALL AMOUNT THAT DID SPILL.  THE WAREHOUSEMAN WAS INSTRUCTED TO TAKE SAFEPRECAUTIONS NEXT TIME AND HE WAS ADVISED THAT HE SHOULD HAVE ORIGINALLY TAKENTHIS DRUM OFF THE PALLET AND USED A DRUM TRUCK TO TRANSFER THE FREIGHT.

DOCK MAN WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING THE FREIGHT ON AN OUTBOUND TRAILER. THE CANISTER WAS PACKAGED IN A WOODEN CRATE AND WAS BEING TRANSPORTED ACROSS THE DOCK ON A FOUR-WHEELED DOCK CART.  THE CAR WAS BEING PUSHED INSIDE THE OUTBOUND TRAILER WHEN THE BOTTOM OF THE CRATE CAME OFF ALLOWING THE CANISTER TO TIP OVER ON ITS SIDE.  THE TOP OF THE CANISTER HAD VENT HOLED WHICH RELEASED PRESSURE INSIDE THE CAINSTER.  WHEN THE CANISTER TIPPED OVER THE LIQUID NITROGEN CAME OUT THE VENT HOLES.  CANISTER WAS UPRIGHTED AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION  SERVICE CENTER ATER APPROVAL FROM THE SHIPPER VIA A TELEPHONE CALL ON 5-25-96. column168: PHYSICAL EVIDENCE INDICATED THAT VEHICLE #1 WAS TRAVELING EAST ON K-9 HWY. EVIDENCE FURTHER INDICATES THAT THE RIGHT SIDE WHEELS OF VEHICLE #1 DROPPED OFF THE RIGHT HAND EDGE OF THE ROADWAY AND TRAVELED DOWN THE SOUTH DITCH FOR APPROXIMATELY 223 FEET.  VEHICLE #1 THEN CAME BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY AND TRAVELED FOR APPROXIMATELY 237 FEET IN A BROAD SLIDE. EVIDENCE INDICATED THAT DURING THE BROAD SLIDE VEHICLE #1 ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  AFTER SLIDING THE 237 FEET VEHICLE #1 ONCE AGAIN LEFT THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND WENT INTO THE SOUTH DITCH WHERE IT STRUCK A CONCRETE CULVERT AND FLIPPED OVER ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE.  VEHICLE #1 CAME TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE WITH THE TRAILER WEDGED INTO A STEEL DRAINAGE CULVERT. ******* DRIVER #1 MADE THE FOLLOWING VERBAL STATEMENT:  "THE TIRES DROPPED OFF THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY AND I LOST CONTROL OF THE TRUCK." ****** IN THIS OFFICERS OPINION THE PRINCIPLE CONTRIBUTING FACTOR OF THIS ACCIDENT WAS THE INABILITY OF DRIVER #1 TO MAINTAIN THE VEHICLE IN A SINGLE LANE OF TRAVEL.  **** NOTE:  ROADWAY HAD BEEN RECENTLY OVERLAYED WITH NEW ASPHALT AND NO CENTER LINES OR EDGEMARKS WERE PRESENT.  ALSO NO PASSING ZONE LINES WERE PRESENT EVEN THOUGH THIS STRETCH OF THE ROADWAY IS SIGNED WITH NO PASSING ZONES. ****** VEHICLE #1 WAS LOADED WITH CRUDE OIL AND WAS PLACARDED.  THE CARRIER RETAINED CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND ITS CONTENTS.  THE AGENTS OF THE CARRIER REQUESTED THAT NO ONE OTHER THAN PROPERLY PROTECTED PEOPLE APPROACH THE VEHICLE.

column168: WHEN THE DRIVER STOPPED AT THE 76 TRUCK STOP IN NEW LISBON, INDIANA, HE NOTICED THAT A SUBSTANCE WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER DOOR. CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA WAS NOTIFIED TO GO TO THE SCENE AND INSPECT THE VEHICLE TO DETERMINE WHAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE SUBSTANCE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE REAR DOOR WAS RAIN WATER, HOWEVER, UPON INSPECTING THE INSIDE TO THE TRAILER, IT WAS NOTED THAT A SUBSTANCE HAD LEAKED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WHICH CAUSED FOAMING. PWI ENVIRONMENTAL WERE CALLED TO INVESTIGATE. UPON INSPECTION BY PWI, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM A PALLET THAT CONTAINED 5 GALLON PAILS OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL. HOWEVER, PWI COULD NOT DETERMINE THE PRODUCT UNTIL SUCH TIME THAT THE PALLET WAS UNLOADED AND THE PAIL IDENTIFIED. PWI TEMPORARILY CONFINED THE SPILL TO THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO PWI'S FACILITY FOR OFF LOADING, DETERMINING SUBSTANCE WHICH LEAKED, DECONTAMINATION OF TRAILER AND RE-LOADING OF THE PRODUCT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A NAIL HEAD IN THE PALLET PIERCED THE BOTTOM OF THE 5 GALLON PAIL. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT WHEN LOADING THIS TYPE OF CARGO ONTO WOODEN SKIDS THAT A DOUBLE WALLED CARDBOARD LINER BE USED BETWEEN THE SKID AND THE PLASTIC PAIL BOTTOMS.

column168: ON 4/20/96, ELECTROPLATING FILTERPRESS SOLIDS WERE SHIPPED IN 11HH2 INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINER WHICH ARE SPECIFIED FOR SOLID MATERIAL. APPARENTLY, DURING TRANSPORTATION, SOME VISCOUS MATERIAL LEACHED FROM THE CONTAINERIZED WASTE MASS IN ONE OF THE CONTAINER.  IN ADDITION, DURING HANDLING AND/OR TRANSPORTATION, THE CONTAINER'S POLYETHYLENE INNER LINER EITHER FAILED OR A HOLE (DUE TO PUNCTURE OR CHAFTING) ALLOWED SOME OF THE VISCOUS MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE CONTAINER.  AFTER A FEW DAYS, WHILE THE WASTE WAS IN 10-DAY STORAGE, LIQUID BEGAN TO LEAK OUT OF THE BOX THROUGH A SMALL HOLE WHICH FORMED IN A BOTTOM CORNER OF THE BOX.  DURING A 10-DAY INSPECTION AT 13:30 ON 5/6/96, AN EMPLOYEE OF AETS DISCOVERED LIQUID ON THE ASPHALT OF THE PARKING LOT UNDER THE TRUCK.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED UNDER THE TRUCK TO ABSORB THE LIQUID AND AETS CONTACTED ENVIROTECH SYSTEM, INC. (ESI, TRANSPORTER ONE) TO INFORM THEM THAT ONE OF THEIR CLIENT'S CONTAINERS WAS LEAKING.  REPRESENTATIVE FROM ESI ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 15:30 TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL AND STABLIZE THE LEAKING CONTAINER.  THE LIQUID IN THE CONTAINER WAS SOLIDIFIED AND A VISQUEEN "DIAPER" WAS PLACED AROUND THE BOX TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING. THE TRAILER WAS THEN CLEANED. THE ASPHALT UNDER THE TRUCK WAS ALSO CLEANED, THIN LAYERS FROM EACH OF THE THREE SMALL SPILL AREA WERE REMOVED AND SAMPLES FROM THE THREE AREA WAS COLLECTED TO VERIFY CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILL.  ON 5/8/96, THE "DIAPERED" BOX AND THE FOUR NON-LEAKING BOXES WERE PLACED IN A 20 CUBIC YARD BOX TO ENSURE CONTAINMENT AND THE WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE TSDF.  ON 5/20/96, ANALYTICAL RESULTS WERE OBTAINED FOR THE SPILL AREA.  ONE OF THE SITES HAD A TCLP LEVEL FOR CHROMUM AT 6.8 MG/L (ppm).  AS A RESULT, FURTHER ASPHALT WILL BE REMOVED AND THE SPILL AREA WIL BE RESAMPLED.

column168: OUR GASOLINE TANKER HIT A STAKED-TRUCK WHO RAN A RED LIGHT.  THE POLICE REPORT (ENCLOSED) STATES AS WELL AS 5 WITNESS THAT IT WAS CLEARLY NOT OUR DRIVER FAULT.  OUR DRIVER (HAROLD BARRINGER) HAD BEEN ON DUTY 1.5 HOURS AND HAD 32.75 HOURS OFF DUTY BEFORE STARTING THIS SHIFT.  OUR VEHICLE TURNED OVER AND RIPPED OPEN SPILLING 4300 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIAN (OUR EMREGENCY RESPONSE CONTACT) WAS ON THE SCENE IN 5 MINUTES MINIMIZING ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.  IDEM HAD BEEN SATISIFIED WITH OUT CLEANUP, RECOVERY, AND DISPOSAL.  STATE POLICE INSPECTED OUR VEHICLE AND FOUND NOTHING WRONG.  LOCAL FEDERAL DOT OFFICIALS INSPECTED OUR 306 A GAS TANKER AND FOUND THAT ALL PRODUCT RETENTION DEVICES FUNCTIONED PROPERLY.  OUR TANKER SKIN WAS RIPPED OPEN DUE TO THE TURNOVER.  THERE WAS NO FIRE AND NO DEATHS.  THE ONLY INJURY WAS TO OUR DRIVER WHO SUFFERED A BROKEN PELVIS AND 3 BROKEN RIBS.

MAY 17, 1996, AT 8:06 P.M., I WAS PAGED BY OUR ANSWERING SERVICE.  I CALLED THE ANSWERING SERVICE AT 8:09PM AND TALKED TO AN OPERATOR BY THE NAME OF CARLOS, HE STATED THAT HE DID NOT HAVE A CALL FOR ME AND CHECKED WITH THE OTHER OPERATORS AND SAID THEY HAD NO CALLS FOR ME, THAT I WAS PAGED BY MISTAKE.  AT 8:24PM, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM OUR ANSWERING SERVICE FROM AN OPERATOR BY THE NAME OF PEPPI.  HE INFORMED ME THAT THE LEBANON FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED AND SAID, "FLAMGAS HAS A LEAK AT THEIR RAIL STORAGE FACILITY ON BADDOUR PARKWAY AND THAT SOMEONE IS NEEDED ON SCENE TO OPEN THE GATE AND CONTAIN THE LEAK."  I THEN CALLED THE LEBANON  FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND WAS TOLD TO GET THERE A.S.A.P.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT 8:44 PM BADDOUR PARKWAY WAS SHUT DOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF MILE ON EACH SIDE OF THE FACILITY AND THE PRO BOWL WEST HAD BEEN EVACUTED.  I WAS THEN TOLD THE LEAK WAS ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE FACILITY AT THE COMPRESSORS.  I WALKED TO COMPRESSORS AND OBSERVED A LEAK OF LIQUID PROPANE AT THE FIRST COMPRESSOR.  THE EMERGENCY PERSONELL HAD ALREADY MANAGED TO GET THRU THE FENCE AND START TO TURN OFF THE VALVES.  I OBSERVED THE LEAK TO BE AT THE HOSE OF THE FLEX JOINT AT THE CLAMP COUPLING.  I PROCEEDED TO CUT OFF ALL VALVING AND BLED LIQUID FROM THE COMPRESSOR.  THE EMERGENCY TEAM AND I THEN WENT ACROSS THE STREET TO CHECK THE STORAGE TANKS AND TO CUT THE PIPELINE CAPTIAN CHARLIE ALSUP, THAT THE GATES WERE FOUND TO BE OPEN UPON THEIR ARRIVAL.  I CHECKED THE LOCKS AND POINTED OUT TO THEM THAT THE LOCK WAS LEFT OPEN BY THE CITY OF LEBANON EMPLOYEES, AS OUR LOCK WAS LOCKED AND SECURE.  AFTER WE TURNED OFF ALL PIPELINE VALVING AND SECURED THE GATE, BADDOUR PARKWAY WAS THEN OPENED TO TRAFFIC.  IT WAS CLOSED OFF APPROXIMATELY ONE AND ONE HALF HOURS. THE PROBLEM APPARENTLY RESULTED FROM THE VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE BEING LEFT ON, THE CHECK VALVE FAILING, ALLOWING LIQUID PROPANE TO MIGRATE TO THE COMPRESSORS AND TEMPERATURES BEING IN THE LOW NINETIES THAT DAY AND THE LIQUID EXPANDING.  THEN, AFTER SUNDOWN THE CONTRACTION CAUSED THE LEAK.  MAY 20, 199, FLAM GAS REPLACED THE TWO FLEX HOSES AND THE CHECK VALVE TO KEEP THIS FROM REOCCURING.  THIS WILL ALSO BE COVERED IN OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING, SCHEDULED ON MAY 21, 1996.  UPON RECOMMENDATIONS BY CHIEF PRESTON AND CAPTAIN ALSUP, I WILL ARRANGE A WALK THRU OF ALL OUR FACILITIES IN LEBANON TO MAKE THEM FAMILIAR WITH THE LOCATIONS OF VALVING AND EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVES.  THESE DIAGRAMS WILL BE PROVIDED TO ALL EMERGENCY PERSONNELL.  TO MY KNOWLEDGE THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGE AND THIS WAS NOT REPORTED TO ANY OTHER EMERGENCY AGENCY.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY MORNING MAY 1, 1996 AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 AM MY PARTNER BILL MEDLEY WAS ALERTED THAT A NATIONAL OIL TANKER BEING PULLED BY  DOUG BUTLER HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT ALONG U.S. HIGHWAY 71 IN NEVADA, MO.  WE PROCEEDED TOWARDS THE ACCCIDENT SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00AM.  ALONG THE WAY WE MET UP WITH 2 EMPLOYEES FROM THE NATIONAL OIL SHOP, RUSSELL PENDLETON AND MIKE HOLMAN.  WE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT AROUND 6:45 AM AND FOUND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER STILL RESTING ON IT'S PASSENGERS SIDE IN THE GRASSY AREA BETWEEN THE NORTH BOUND LANE OF 71 AND THE ON-RAMP ROAD LEADING TO THE NORTHBOUND LANES.  ASPHALT OIL WAS RUNNING WEST FROM THIS SITE THROUGH A WHISTLE UNDER THE SOUTH BOUND LANES OF 71, THEN EXTENDED ON WEST THROUGH A DITCH LEADING A TUNNEL WHICH WENT UNDERNEATH THE ON-RAMP ACCESS ROAD TO 71 NORTH.  USING A COUPLE OF DUMPTRUCK LOADS OF DIRT, THE NEVADA FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD SUCCESSFULLY STOPPED THE FLOW JUST BEYOND THIS TUNNEL, PREVENTING ANY OIL FROM TRAVELING INTO AN ADJACENT OUTER ROAD WHISTLE WHICH LED TO A SMALL STREAM THAT FEEDS THE NEVADA CITY PARK POND. THE TOTAL DISTANCE THAT THE ASPHALT OIL HAD TRAVELED WAS ESTIMATED TO BE AROUND 1/8TH OF A MILE.  AS WE TRAVELED TO THE SITE THAT MORNING IN OUR SEPARATE VEHICLES, BILL WAS IN CONTACT WITH THE NEVADA FIRE DEPARTMENT BY CELLULAR PHONE AND WAS INFORMED OF THE ABOVE MENTIONED OIL FLOW.  TALKING TO ME BY RADIO IT WAS DECIDED THAT WE WOULD NEED A VACCUM TRUCK TO COME TO THE SITE AND REMOVE THE OIL FROM THE DITCHES.  I TOLD HIM TO HAVE SOMEONE FROM NATIONAL OIL CONTACT MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL OUT OF CARTHAGE AND HAVE THEM SEND US THEIR VACUUM TRUCK.  A MISUNDERSTANDING ENSUED AND DUE TO THE FACT THAT MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL WOULD NOT BE DOING THE ENTIRE CLEANUP, WE WERE DECLINED THE USE OF THEIR VACUUM TRUCK, BUT PHIL ROSS OF MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL HAD ARRANGED FOR TWO VACCUM TRUCKS FROM HILLBILLY PUMPING AND HAULING OUT OF CATERVILLE, MO TO COME TO THE SCENE.  A TANKER FROM NATIONAL OIL WAS ALSO DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE FOR THE PURPOSE OF OFF LOADING THE REMAINING OIL IN THE WRECKED TANKER.  A LOCAL CONSTRUCTION COMPANY, CARLINI CONSTRUCTION CO., WAS ALSO ON SITE READY TO BEGIN SCRAPING AND DIRT REMOVAL PROCEDURES.  ONCE THE TANKER FROM NATIONAL HAD ARRIVED, RUSSELL, MIKE AND DRIVER RON BRANDT BEGAN PUMPING OFF THE REMAINING OIL.  ONCE  THEY REACHED THE POINT WHERE THE TANKER NEEDED TO BE UPRIGHTED TO RETRIEVE THE REST, THE WRECKER COMPANY ON SITE PROCEEDED TO SET THE TRUCK AND TANKER BACK ON IT'S WHEELS.  ONCE IN THE UPRIGHT POSITION, THE REMAINING OIL WAS PUMPED OFF AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND TAKEN TO BRINES WRECKER COMPANY IN SPRINGFIELD, MO.  THIS OIL WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE MISSOURI HIGHWAY AND TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT FACILITY IN NEVADA AND PUMPED OFF INTO THEIR STORAGE TANK.  RON STATED THAT HE THOUGHT THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2500 GALLONS OF OIL. MANIFESTS INDICATE THAT DOUG WAS HAULING 5400 GALLONS AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, LEAVING AN ESTIMATED 2900

ENVIRONMENTAL WORKS, INC. (EWI) WAS RETAINED BY TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT COMPANY (TRISM) OF JOPLIN, MISSOURI ON MAY 14, 1996 TO CONDUCT THE CLEANUP OF AN APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLON HAZARDOUS WASTE FERRIC CHLORIDE LIQUID SPILL. THE HAZARDOUS CONSTITUENTS OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL CONSIST OF CORROSIVITY (PH GREATER THAN 1.5), CADMIUM, CHROMIUM AND LEAD. THE SPILL OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 18:45 ON MAY 13, 1996, AND RESULTED FROM ONE LEAKING 55-GALLON DRUM WHICH WAS LOCATED IN A SEMI-TRAILER. THE SPILL WAS ALSO REPORTED TO THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES (MDNR) AT 10:30 ON MAY 14, 1996 AND WAS ASSIGNED INCIDENT NUMBER 960514-1035-EJS. THE SPILL WAS ALSO REPORTED TO THE UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCIES NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (EPA NRC) AT 10:40 ON MAY 14, 1996 AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT NUMBER 341306. THIS REPORT INCLUDES DOCUMENTATION FOR ACTIONS TAKEN TO REMEDIATE THE IMPACTED CONCRETE, ASPHALT, SOILS AND SEMI-TRUCK AND TRAILER AT THE SPILL LOCATION. IMPACTED MATERIAL AND SPENT CLEANING MATERIALS DISPOSAL IS ALSO DOCUMENTED IN THIS REPORT.** ON THE NIGHT OF MAY 13, 1996, TRISM PERSONNEL OBSERVED A LEAKING 55-GALLON DRUM IN A TRISM TRAILER PARKED AT THE SUBJECT PROPERTY. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED AND REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. ALL OTHER CONTAINERS ON THE TRAILER WERE ALSO REMOVED. THE SEMI-TRUCK AND TRAILER AND THREE AREAS OF THE GROUND SURFACE WERE IMPACTED BY THE SPILL ON THE SUBJECT SITE. THESE THREE AREAS CONSIST OF THE CONCRETE UNDER A CANOPY AT THE TRUCK INSPECTION AREA, AN ASPHALT AREA AT THE APPROXIMATE CENTER OF THE TRAILER PARKING AREA AND AT THE NORTHWEST CORNER OF THE TRAILER PARKING AREA. ** ON MAY 14, 1996, EWI PERSONNEL MOBILIZED TO THE SITE TO EXCAVATE AND CLEAN IMPACTED AREAS. IMPERMEABLE SURFACES INCLUDING CONCRETE, SOME ASPHALT SURFACES, SEMI-TRUCK SURFACES AND TRAILER SURFACES WERE CLEANED BY HAND USING A D-LEAD SOLUTION (CLEANER AND DEGREASER FOR LEAD AND OTHER HEAVY METALS), RAGS AND MOPS. THE USED RAGS, MOPS AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE) WERE PLACED IN A 55-GALLON DRUM FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL. IMPACTED ASPHALT AT THE APPROXIMATE CENTER OF THE TRAILER PARKING AREA WAS SEVERELY CRACKED OR NON-EXISTENT, THEREFORE, A LOCAL BACKHOE CONTRACTOR PROVIDED EXCAVATION EQUIPMENT TO ASSIST IN REMOVAL OF THE ASPHALT AND SOIL. APPROXIMATELY 1.5 CUBIC YARDS OF ASPHALT AND SOIL WERE CONTAINERIZED IN 55-GALLON DRUMS AND ONE OVERPACK DRUM AND STORED ON SITE FOR FUTURE DISPSOAL. PHOTOGRAPHIC DOCUMENTATION OF THE EXCAVATED AREA BEFORE AND AFTER CLEANUP IS INCLUDED IN APPENDIX A. ** UPON REMOVAL OF THE IMPACTED ASPHALT AND SOIL, ONE COMPOSITE SOIL SAMPLE (COMPOSITE OF THREE GRABS) WAS COLLECTED APPROXIMATELY EIGHT-INCHES BELOW LAND SURFACE AND ANALYZED FOR PH BY EPA METHOD 9045C AND TCLP CADMIUM, CHROMIUM, AND LEAD BY EPA METHOD 1311/7130, 7190, 7420. ONE COMPOSITE SOIL SAMPLE WAS ALSO COLLECTED FROM THE STOCKPILED MATERIAL IN THE STORAGE DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL ACCEPTANCE. THE STOCKPILED SOIL WAS ANALYZED FOR PH AND TH

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DURING THE SORT WE FOUND THE PACKAGE TO BE EMITTING A STRONG GASOLINE ODOR.  UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND A FUEL PUMP THAT HAD NOT BEEN DRAINED.  THE BOX REPLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND REMOVED FROM THE SORT. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AS WAS THE SHIPPER.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FREIGHT HAS BEEN INSPECTED & RELEASED BY THE FAA.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO FAX A DG DECLARATION SO THE FREIGHT COULD BE SENT TO IT'S DESTINATION.

DRUM WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED.  APPARENTLY THE SEAL ON THE LID OF ONE OF THE DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT SECURED.  THIS RESULTED IN A SLIGHT LEAKAGE AROUND THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE EXCESS WAS CLEANED UP AND THE TOP OF THE DRUM WAS RESEALED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

ADDITIONALLY THE CAN EXHIBITED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS AND LABELS THAT THE OUTER CONTAINER DID NOT FOR ALL INTENTS PURPOSES THIS CONSTITUTED AND UNDECLARED COMMODITY AS THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS AND LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER CONAINER NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE IN ASSOCIATION WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA AND RELEASED.

column168: ON 5/22/96 AT APPROXIMATELY 0235 HOURS, A SHIPMENT OF GASOLINE WAS REPORTED LEAKING IN THE HAZMAT SORT BUILDING OF OUR FACILITY AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OH 45`177.  I, KAEN NICHOLS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX, AIR INC. 9SAM ADDRESS) INVESITGATED THE SHIPMENT AND REPACKAGED IT IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY PACKAGED AND DECLARED BUT LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 10 ML DUE TO INSUFFICIENT ULAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.

ON 5/30/96 AT APPROXIMATELY 0242 HOURS, DIANE FIGUAROA/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OH  45177 INVESTIGATION A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUT SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS. THE SHIPMENT WAS A1 OR METAL CAN WITH A FRICTION-TYPE CLOSURE THAT WAS NOT SECURED CLOSED WITH POSITIVE MEANS.  THIS METAL CAN WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT HAD NO MARKINGS OR LABELS AFFIXED NOR DID A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.  THE AIR WAYBILL ATTACHED TO THE FIBERBOARD BOX INDICATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS A HAZARDOUS SAMPLE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INFORMATION FROM THIS SHIPPER.  THE INFORMATION PROVIDED WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET INDICATING THE PRODUCT HAD A FLASHPONT OF 140 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN TURNED IN TO THE FAA FOR INSPECTION.  WE THEN RECEIVED A LETTER FROM THE SHIPPER STATING THAT THERE WAS AN ERROR IN THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET AND THE FLASH POINT FOR THE MIXTURE SHOULD BE 180 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT.  THE SHIPMENT IS IN OUT HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA AND ADEQUATE INFORMATION FROM THE SHIPPER TO LEGALLY MOVE THE SHIPMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER AS REQUESTED.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON 5/28/96 A SPILL WAS REPORTED WITH AN ODOR AT ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH  45177.  UPON ARRIVAL WE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH WAS EMITTING AN ODOR.  AFTER OPENING THE FIBERBOARD BOX WE DISCOVERED THAT A PAINT PRODUCT WHICH WAS IN A PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY 3 OZS WAS LEAKING.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS POSSIBLE CLOSURE FAILURE.  THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED ONE METAL RECEPTACLE/1 QUART SIZE AND 4 PLASTIC RECEPTACLE / PINT SIZE.  ONLY ONE OF THE 1 PINT SIZE RECEPTACLES WAS LEAKING.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL LABLED AND MARKINGS APPLIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON 05/08/96 AT 1330 HOURS, SAHM CARMAN WAS NOTIFIED BY THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD DISPATCHER THAT WYNNE FIRE DEPT. REPORTED TANKCAR DOWX 4435 LEAKING. SAHM CARMAN RESPONDED TO WYNNE ARRIVING AT 1500 HOURS. UPON ARRIVAL SAHM CARMAN MET WITH WYNNE FIRE DEPARTMENT CHIEF DAN CURTNER. CHIEF CURTNER ADVISED THAT RESIDENCE CLOSE TO THE RAILYARD REPORTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE YARD. CHIEF CURTER OBSERVED A LIQUID UNDERNEATH TANKCAR DOWX 4435, A RESIDUE LOAD OF ALLYL CHLORIDE. WYNNE FIRE DEPARTMENT SPRAYED WATER AND FOAM ON THIS LIQUID AND THEN COVERED IT WITH SAND. AFTER COMMUNICATING WITH CHIEF CURNER, SAHM CARMAN INSPECTED TANKCAR DOWX 4435. SAHM CARMAN REPORTED ALL LIQUID AND VAPOR PLUGS SECURE AND NO SIGN OF A LEAK UNDERNEATH THE DOME OF THE TANCAR. THE INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS CHECKED ON DOWX 4435 AND IT READ 15 LBS. THIS TANCAR CAME EQUIPPED WITH A 75 LB. SAFETY VALVE. IT WAS SAHM CARMAN OPINION THAT DOWX 4435 WAS NOT THE ORIGIN OF THE ODOR. CARMAN INSPECTED THE TANKCAR NEXT TO DOWX 4435. THIS TANKCAR CELX 23245, A RESIDUE CAR OF METHYL ACRYLATE, WAS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. THE 2 INCH LIQUID PLUG ON THE TANKCAR WAS LOOSE, AND THE ODOR WAS ESCAPING. THE PLUG WAS SECURED BY SAHM CARMAN AND THE PROBLEM RECTIFIED. FIRE CHIEF CURTNER REPORTED TWO HOMES EVACUATED DUE TO THE ODOR. CHIEF CURTNER ALSO REPORTED ONE PERSON WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT. DON BAILEY, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS IN MEMPHIS, WAS ALSO AT THE SCENE AND REPORTED THAT CELX HAD JUST BEEN RELEASED FROM CPS CHEMICAL IN WEST MEMPHIS NAD HE HAD SPOKEN TO MIKE CHAPMAN, OF CPS CHEMICAL, MAKING HIM AWARE OF THE SITUATION. SAHM CARMAN ALSO REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO CHEMTREC AND ROBERTA CAVALLI, OF HOECHST CELANESE, THE NEXT DESTINATION OF THE TANKCAR. ON 05/09/96 SAHM CARMAN NOTIFIED RICHARD MERRITT OF PC & E, ADVISING OF THE INCIDENT.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT SALT LAKE UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR UP 70091 LOADED CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED LOOSE MANWAY COVER. MGR. RODABOUGH INSPECTED THE GASKET AND FOUND IT TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION, HE THEN SECURED THE MANWAY USING A 36" PIPE WRENCH. THE CAR WAS RELEASED AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED MRS. TRACY JACKSON FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND SHIPPER AMOCO OIL MR. GARY ZIMMER ALSO INFORMED REGARDING SITUATION.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HRS., PDT. THAT MR. JIM LESLIE, SAFETY DIRECTOR, PRECISION MACHINE, TACOMA, WASHINGTON HAD ADVISED CHEMTREC THAT TANK CAR HOKX 8306 HAD BEEN OBSERVED WITH A VAPOR AT THE TOP OF THE CAR.  TANKCAR HOKX 8306 LOCATED (OLD TRACK #19) ON THE TACOMA MUNICIPAL BELT LINE LEAD TRACK, BEHIND PRECISION MACHINE, TACOMA, WA.  UPON ARRIVAL, LIBBY DISCOVERED THAT A UNION PACIFIC SWITCH CREW HAD JUST PULLED THE RAILCARS FROM THE TMBL LEAD AND PLACED THE TANK CAR IN QUESTION INTO TRACK 8, FIFE YARD, FIFE, WA.  AT ARRIVAL FIFE YARD, HE FURTHER DISCOVERED THAT CHEMTREC, ALSO NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE, OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CORP., TACOMA, WA. IN REGARD TO THIS INCIDENT AND WAS MET NEAR TANKCAR HOKX 8306, PLACARDED CORROSIVE 8, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION, BY GARY SELLERS, TEAM LEADER, OXYCHEM"S CHLOREP TEAM, FROM OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CORP., TACOMA, WA.  HE ADVISED THEY FOUND THE CAP OFF THE WELL LINE AND ALL 3 NUTS MISSING FROM THE BOLTS SECURING THE RUPTURE DISC HOUSING.  HOWEVER, DID NOT DETECT ANY VAPOR AT THAT POINT IN TIME.  HE FURTHER STATED CORRECTED AND SECURED BOTH WELL LINE AND RUPTURE DISC HOUSING.  IN ADDITION MR. SELLERS ADVISED THEY CONDUCTED AN INSPECTION OF 2 OTHER TANKCARS ADJACENT TO THE HOKX 8306 AND FOUND THE CAP OFF THE VENT VALVE ON HOKX 8277 (NO VAPOR OR RELEASE OF PRODUCT DETECTED) WHICH HIS TEAM ALSO CORRECTED.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT TANKCAR HOKX 8277 WAS NOT IDENTIFIED IN THE INITIAL NOTIFICATION FROM MR. LESLIE, PRECISION MACHINE OR CHEMTREC.  FURTHER, HOKX 8277 WAS SHIPPED BY THE SAME SHIPPER AND CONSIGNED TO THE SAME CONSIGNEE AS HOKX 8306.  AFTER ALL THE REPAIRS HAD BEEN COMPLETED LIBBY  AGAIN CONTACTED MR. LESLIE, PRECISION MACHINE, TACOMA AND THANKED HIM FOR HIS CONERN AND PLACING HIS CALL TO CHEMTREC.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED THE WEST END SWITCH CREW OBSERVED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE BEING HANDLED IN A CUT OF CARS DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  CAR KCCX 2615 WAS RECEIVED ON INTERCHANGE FROM THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD AT COLTON, 2331 HOURS, THURSDAY, MAY 9, 1996, AND ARRIVED YERMO IN THE CNYR-09, 0400 HOURS, FRIDAY, MAY 10, 1996.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND ASSEMBLY WITH BAFFLE, WHICH MOUNTED ADJACENT TO THE MANWAY, WITHIN THE WORK PLATFORM AREA, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED:  THE DISC RETAINER HAD BEEN INSTALLED UPSIDE DOWN; ONE OF THE FOUR RETAINER STUDS WAS BROKEN OFF; THE REMAINING THREE 1/2 INCH BY 7/8 INCH STUD NUTS HAD BEEN OVER TIGHTENED, REQUIRING THE USE OF A TORQUE MULIPLIER TO REMOVE THEM.  IT APPEARS SOMEONE ATTEMPTED TO ACCESS THE BURST DISC AT SOME PRIOR POINT, AND DUE TO THE NUTS BEING OVER TIGHTENED, BROKE THE STUD OFF.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS COMPLETELY DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 100 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EXCEPTIONS TO THE CAR AND THEY MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR SHOPPED AT OGDEN, WHERE THE NECSSARY REPAIRS COULD BE MADE TO THE SAFETY VENT.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES; THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION; AND THE SOUTHERN PACIFICRAILROAD FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT WEST END SWITCH CREW OBSERVED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION. CAR ITLX 220814 WAS RECEIVED ON INTERCHANGE FROM THE ATCHISON, TOPEKA AND SANTA FE RAILROAD AT BARSTOW, 1330 HOURS FRIDAY, MAY 10, 1996, AND ARRIVED YERMO IN THE LN59-10, 1400 HOURS, DATE.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY AREA OF THE CAR.  DEVELOPED ALL 8 OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  THE COVER PLATE WAS OPENED TO INSPECT THE GASKET, WHICH APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WAS PROPERLY SECURED BY TIGHTENING ALL 8 OF THE SWING BOLTS WITH AN APPROPRIATE WRENCH.  THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ASSURE PROPER SECUREMENT, AND THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTEC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES; AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: MEMPHIS REPAIR TRACK FOREMAN GARY DYE NOTED LIQUID SPILING FROM TANK CAR GATX 38624 WHEN MOVED, FOREMAN DYE ISOLATED CAR AT REPAIR TRACK AND NOTIFIED MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY C. HILL WHO RESPONDED.  MGR. HILL'S INSPECTION REVEALED A FAILED B.S.&B.  100 PSI FRANGIBLE DISC.  A NEW B.S.&B. 100 PSI FRANGIBLE DISC WAS INSTALLED IN SAFETY VENT.  SAFETY VENT WAS LOCATED OUTSIDE WORKING PLATFORM, WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH BAFFLE. CAR WAS WASHED DOWN WITH WATER AND RELEASED.  CHEMTREC'S TRACY JACKSON ASSIGNED REPORT NO.44148 TO THIS INCIDENT.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE DID RESPOND WITH PHONE CALL.

column168: ON 051296 AT APPROXIMATELY 930PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER WAS NOTIFIED BY CORRIDOR MANAGER, BILLY SIMMONS THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING IN DE QUINCY, LA.  INITIAL REPORTS INDICATED THE CAR WAS ON THE KCS RAILROAD, BUT THE CAR HAD NOT YET BEEN INTERCHANGED.  THE LOCAL POLICE HAD CALLED THE CONSIGNEE TO ASK FOR THEIR ASSISTANCE.  THEY SENT A TECHNICIAN WHO WAS UNABLE TO HELP.  REEDER ARRIVED ABOUT 1 AM. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE O-RINGS IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WERE DEFECTIVE.  THE SHIPPER HAD HIRED EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO RESPOND ALSO.  CHIP DAY OF EMTECH AND REEDER WERE ABLE TO CHANGE THE O-RINGS AND STOP THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS SENT ON TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER DELAY.  REEDER ASKED THE SHIPPER TO THOROUGHLY EXAMINE THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND REPLACE THE O-RINGS AGAIN BEFORE RELOADING THE CAR.  CHEMTREC WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 051396 AT APPROXIMATELY 330PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, STEVE DOLEAL THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS "HISSING" FROM THE TOP.  REEDER WAS OUT OF TOWN AND COULD NOT RESPOND IMMEDIATELY.  REEDER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER HIRED EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO RESPOND.  CHIP DAY OF EMTECH INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT ALL EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THAT FOUR OF THE EIGHT WERE LESS THAT HAND TIGHT.  ALL BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT SALT LAKE UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR KCCX3145, LOADED TANKCAR OF SULFURIC ACID AND NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR.  INSPECTION REVEALED LEAK COMING FROM THE "2 DISCHARGE PIPE CAP.  APPARENTLY THE CAR HAD PRESSURED UP DUE TO THE HIGHER THAN AVERAGE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE, FORCING THE PRODUCT UP THE PIPE WHERE IT LEAKED.  MGR. RODABOUGH RELEASED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR THROUGH THE AIR CONNECTION AND REMOVED THE CAP, FINDING NO GASKET.  MGR. RODABOUGH APPLIED A GASKET AND TAPED THE BARREL OF THE PIPE AND REPLACED THE CAP.  THE CAR WAS WASHED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WATER AND RELEASED.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED AND FURNISHED WITH DETAILS, THE SHIPPER KENNECOTT UTAH COOPER MR. WAYNE STOCKEBRAND ALSO INFORMED.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR GATX86476, LOADED TANKCAR OF PHOSPHORIC ACID, NOTED PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE SAFETY VENT RUPTURE DISC BROKEN, MGR. RODABOUGH APPLIED A BS&B 100# DISC TO THE SAFETY VENT LOCATED OUTSIDE THE WORK PLATFORM.  THE CAR WAS WASHED DOWN WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WATER AND RELEASED.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED MR. JEFF BOTWENIC FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE #44240.  THE SHIPPER J.R. SIMPLOT NOTIFIED BY CHEMTREC.  RETURNED THEIR CALL, INFORMING THEM OF DETAILS.

UPRR MTO JERRY REPORTED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 200104 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE CAR HAD JUST ARRIVED AND WAS IN TRACK 101, CENTENNIAL YARD. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE TOP-OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPEN 1/4 TURN AND THE BOTTOM PIPE CAP LOOSE.   SEAL #STAN TRANS. INC. 14750 WAS REMOVED AND THE FITTINGS WERE TIGHTENED.  THE LEAKAGE STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 0855 HRS., DATE.  SEAL #UPB 203024 WAS APPLIED TO SECURE THE CAR.  BOB WIBLE, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AT 1055 HRS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1930 HRS ON 5-22-96, SPECIAL AGENT LARRY CAMPBELL HAD CONTACTED CTS MGR LERCH.  HE ADVISED THAT AT 1900HRS, CAR FOREMAN HERB LARSON HAD REPORTED TANK  CAR ACFX 200104 LOCATED ON WEST DEPARTMENT TRACK 10 TO BE LEAKING. UPON ARRIVAL AT LOCATION, MR. CAMPBELL NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A RATE 50 DROPS A MINUTE, WITH NO DRAINS OR WATER WAYS AFFECTED.  INSPECTION OF CAR BY MR. CAMPBELL REVEALED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO BE OPEN 1-1/2 TURNS.  UPON TIGHTENING OF VALVE THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  UPON ARIVAL MGR. LERCH, FURTHER INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUT VALVE CAP LOOSE 1/4 TURN AND PACKING GLAND NUT LOOSE 1 1/4 TURNS.  UPON CORRECTION OF ALL EXCEPTIONS CAR WAS RELEASED WITHOUT FURTHER DELAY.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP REQUIRED DUE TO PRODUCT EVAPORATION UPON CONTACTED WITH THE GROUND AND OUTSIDE ATOMOSPHERE.  SEALS PROTECTING:  COMBINATION HOUSING STAN TRANS INC. #14749, REPLACED BY UPC-73073.  TOP OPERATED BOTTOM VALVE UPB-203024, REPLACED BY UPC-73074.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1235 HRS. ON 5/22/96, SR. SPECIAL AGENT T.J. BOUDREAUXRECEIVED A CALL VIA RADIO FROM YARDMASTER JOE KASS WHO ADVISED THAT WHILE TRAIN AVLID 22 WAS BEING MADE UP ON THE #1 MAIN LINE A SPRR CARMAN AT ABOUT 1230 HRS. DETECTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM ONE OF THE TANK CARS.  AT 1240 HRS. ON 5/22/96, AGENT BOUDREAUX LOCATED TANK CAR ACFX 18727 THAT WAS LEAKING UNDER THE THEROMETER WELL CAP.  A FULL FACE RESPIRATOR WAS WORN WHILE TIGHTENING THE CAP. IT APPEARED TO BE TIGHT. HOWEVER, THE LEAK CONTINUED WITH VAPOR DISIPATING IN THE WIND.  AGENT BOUDREAUX ALSO NOTED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE AND BOTH LIQUID VALVE PLUGS WERE LOOSE AND ABLE TO TURN BY HAND.  THESE THREE VALVE PLUGS WERE TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH.  AGENT BOUDREAUX CONTACTED CTS REGIONAL MANAGER T.M. ROBINSON WHO ADVISED THAT HE WOLUD RESPOND TO INCIDENT FROM HIS PRESENT LOCATION, ALEXANDRIA, LA.  AGENT BOUDREAUX CONTACTED AVONDALE YARDMASTER KEN WHITE AND REQUESTED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 18727 BE CUT OUT OF TRAIN SO AS NOT TO CAUSE ANY DELAY OF DEPARTURE AND MOVE THE TANK CAR TO A SAFE LOCATION AWAY FROM WORKING PERSONNEL.  WHITE HAD THE TANK CAR MOVED TO THE AVONDALE TRACK WHICH MADE THE TANK CAR EASILY ACCESSABLE.  THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT:  1305 HRS. LOUISIANA STATE POLICE ANN-ITEM 96-2011 LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.  1310 HRS. JEFFERSON PARISH FIRE DEPARTMENT & SHERIFF'S OFFICE.  1330 HRS. TRI AD CHEMICAL - STEVE MISTRETTA.  THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES ARRIVED ON THE SCENE: 1315 HRS. JEFFERSON  PARISH, BRIDGE CITY FIRE DEPT.  1330 HRS. LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, HAZ MAT TROOPER RAY MYERS.  1400 HRS. DEQ, GROUND QUALITY LUKE PIRANIO.  1430 DEQ, AIR QUALITY DANNY ODEM & SCOTT AVANCINO.  1500 HRS. TRI AD CHEMICAL, STEVE MISTRETTA.  AGENT BOUDREAUX ALONG WITH MISTRETTA ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE LEAK BY REMOVING THE THEROMETER WELL CAP AND APPLYING A GATE VALVE IN ITS PLACE.   THE VALVE DID NOT WORK BECAUSE IT DID NOT COVER THE WEEP HOLES IN THE THERMOMETER WELL TUBE.  THE CAP WAS REPLACED AND SCREWED DOWN OVER THE WEEP HOLE AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH MYIO HILLARU LEVINER TO MOVE TANK CAR ACFX 18727 ON THE FIRST AVAILABLE TRAIN TO DONALDSONVILLE, LA. FOR REPAIR BY TRI AD CHEMICAL.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 05-23-96 AT APPROXIMATELY 1PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, BRENT LICHTY, THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS SLOSHING LIQUID FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED. LICHTY STATED THAT LIQUID QUICKLY EVAPORATED FROM THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND NO MATERIAL REACHED THE GROUND.  THE TEMPERATURE WAS ABOUT 95F WITH WINDS AT 20MPH.  REEDER ADVISED LICHTY TO ISOLATE THE CAR AND HE WOULD MAKE THE REPAIRS.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER NOTED A STAIN NEAR THE MANWAY COVER.  ALL EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHT.  REEDER REMOVED SEAL HOESCHST CLEANESE 833342 FROM THE MANWAY AND OPENED THE COVER.  THE GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE NEAR THE HINGE.  THE GASKET WAS CRACKED AND HAD SMALL PIECES MISSING AROUND ITS OUTSIDE EDGE.  REEDER FORMED A NEW GASKET FROM GORE-TEXX.  THE COVER WAS SECURED AND RESEALED WITH UNION PACIFIC 483395. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

TANK CAR OBSERVED AT UNION PACIFIC RAILYARD IN LIVONIA, LA. WITH THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING LID OPEN.  UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON NOTIFIED.  AN INSPECTION BY ROBINSON DISCLOSED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG WAS NOT INSTALLED.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF AMMONIA VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM THE OPEN VALVE PORT.  ROBINSON CLOSED THE VALVE, SECURED THE PLUG WITH A SUITABLE WRENCH AND PROPERLY SECURED THE LID OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE CAR CONTINUED ON TO DESTINATION WITH OUT DELAY.  ROBINSON NOTIFIED CHEMTREC'S OE BABOR AND RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. STEVE MISTRETTA OF FIRST MISS FERTILIZER AT DONALDSONVILLE, LA. MISTRETTA WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN BY ROBINSON.  MISTRETTA ADVISED THAT HE WOULD FOLLOWUP WITH APPROPRIATE PLANT PERSONNEL TO AVOID A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS NATURE.

TANK CAR OBSERVED AT UNION PACIFIC RAILYARD IN LIVONIA, LA. WITH THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING LID OPEN.  UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON NOTIFIED.  AN INSPECTION BY ROBINSON DISCLOSED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG WAS NOT INSTALLED.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF AMMONIA VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM THE OPEN VALVE PORT.  ROBINSON CLOSED THE VALVE, SECURED THE PLUG WITH A SUITABLE WRENCH AND PROPERLY SECURED THE LID FOR THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE CAR CONTINUED ON TO DESTINATION WITH OUT DELAY.  ROBINSON NOTIFIED CHEMTREC'S JOE BABOR AND RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. STEVE MISTRETTA OF FIRST MISS FERTILIZER AT DONALDSONVILLE, LA. MISTRETTA WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN BY ROBINSON.  MISTRETTA ADVISED THAT HE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH APPROPRIATE PLANT PERSONNEL TO AVOID A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS NATURE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: S/A, BALLANCE WAS ADVISED BY THE MILPITAS YARD MTO PETE THAT TANKCAR ACFX 86502 WAS IN JONES CHEMICALS AND WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  S/A, BALLANCE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND MADE AN INSPECTION OF THE TANKCAR AND FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BLOWN.  THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED.  THE TANKCAR WAS REMOVED FROM JONES CHEMICALS FOR LATER PICKUP BY THE LOCAL SWITCHER.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE MILPITAS YARD BY THE SWITCHER.  AT THE MILPITAS YARD A POOL WAS CONSTRUCTED BELOW THE TANKCAR AND THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICE AND DENNIS BIGGS OF THE CA PUC WERE ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, PORTLAND, OR., WAS NOTIFIED BY YARDMASTER ROD TARTER, HINKLE YARD HINKLE, OR., THAT TANK GATX61110, HYDROCHLORIC ACID, SPOTTED RECEIVING TRACK #3, HAD PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN SIDE OF TANK CAR.  WHITELEY TRAVELED TO HINKLE AND FOUND FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS CLOSURES/FITTINGS ON CAR.  FOUR BOLT BLIND GLANGE NOTED TWO BOLTS MISSING FLAT WASHERS AND NUTS, TWO BOLTS WITH NUTS NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  EIGHT BOLT FLANGE LOCATED BELOW FOUR BOLT FLANGE NOTED THREE BOLTS/NUTS NOT WRENCH TIGHT ONE OF WHICH COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED OR REMOVED/REPLACED ON ACCOUNT OF CONDITION AND LOCATION.  THREE BOLT/ NUT FLANGE ASSEMBLY SECURES SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY ON CAR WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT. AT TIME OF INSPECTION CAR HAD STOPPED LEAKING AND DUE TO MULTIPLE LOCATIONS LOOSE FITTINGS WAS NOT POSITIVE LEAKING CONDITION HAD BEEN CORRECTED. TRIM UNITS WERE COUPLED TO TANK CAR TO SIMULATE HANDLING WITH NO LEAKS DETECTED.  FOUR BOLTS HINGED FILL HOLE ON TANK  CAR WAS PROTECTED INTACT SEAL WEY 017729. CHEMTREC JOE MILAZZO WAS FURNISHED DETAILS AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT #44503. WEYERHAUSER DALE KOTH WAS PROVIDED DETAILS TUESDAY 05/28/96.

SPECIALIST TUFTS RECEIVED CALL AT 2215 HRS FROM MTO DAVE BRICKNER THAT ARGON CAR #BIGX 1016 WAS LEAKING AT LESPERENCE ST. YARD. SPECIALIST TUFTS NOTIFIED REGIONAL MGR. ROBINSON AND RESPONDED NOTING THAT CAR WAS LEAKING OUT OF CAP ON PRODUCT LINE.  UPON INSPECTION IT WAS NOTED THAT GATE VALVE WAS APPROX 1/8 TURN LOOSE AND KNOCK TIGHT CAP WAS APPROX 1/2 TURN LOOSE. FITTINGS WERE SECURED AND LEAK STOPPED.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED AND SHIPPER CONTACTED TUFTS REMAINED ON SCENE UNTIL ARGON RESIDUE THAWED TO ENSURE LEAK STOPPED AND THEN RELEASED CAR TO DESTINATION.

CONTAINER EMPU 180725, ARRIVE POCATELLO, ID. IN TRAIN MESEZ 24 ON FLAT CAR TTAX 76169, ON MONDAY MAY 28, 1996. THE CAR WAS REPORTED LEAKING BY THE CAR DEPARTMENT. SR. SPL. AGT. HAZ/MAT S. MARTINEZ INSPECTED THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE COMING FROM THE FILLER CAP ON THE TOP OF A 275 GALLON WIRE MESH ENCLOSED TOTE. THE CAP WAS REMOVED AND CLEANED, THE THREADS ON THE TOTE WERE CLEANED AND TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE THREADS PRIOR TO THE CAP BEING SET IN PLACE. THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE ARE DESCRIBED AS A CONCRETE RELEASING AGENT, AND PLACARDED COMBUSTIBLE. THE ORIGINAL TYDEN SEAL WAS REMOVED, SYMONS 10621, AND A NEW CABLE CONE SEAL UP 007807 WAS APPLIED. MRS. T. JACKSON WAS NOTIFIED FROM CHEMTREC AND FURNISHED WITH ALL THE NECESSARY INFORMATION. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C. COPPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED THE SWITCH CREW HAD OBSERVED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP, DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. CAR KCCX 2518 WAS RECEIVED ON INTERCHANGE FROM THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD AT COLTON, 2020 HOURS, SUNDAY, MAY 26, 1996, AND ARRIVED YERMO IN THE CNYR-26, 0500 HOURS, MONDAY, MAY 27, 1996. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND DISCOVERED A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND ASSEMBLY WITH BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSAMBLED, THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES; THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION; AND THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. THE SHIPPER WAS ALSO ADVISED THAT THE FOUR NUTS WHICH SECURE THE RETAINER FOR THE FRANGIBLE DISC, REQUIRED REPLACEMENT AS THEY HAD BEEN ROUNDED OFF, AND COULD ONLY BE REMOVED WITH A PIPE WRENCH.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 053096 AT APPROXIMATELY 1PM BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR, JOHN REED WAS MAKING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF TANK CARS IN THE YARD AT BLOOMINGTON, TEXAS. HE HEARD THE ABOVE CAR HISSING. HE CLIMBED THE CAR BUT DID NOT BREAK THE SEAL. HE REPORTED THE CAR TO THE MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, BRENT LICHTY, WHO STATED THE CAR WAS LEAVING SHORTLY TO BE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE PLANT, RESPONSE PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BASE OF THE VAPOR VALVE. THEY TIGHTENED THE VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THEY ALSO FOUND THE PLUG IN THE B END LIQUID VALVE WAS OUT. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DURING ROUTINE INSPECTIONS, SPECIALIST CTS RICHARD TUFTS NOTED THAT VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM LOOSE MANWAY COVER. SPECIALIST TUFTS TIGHTENED SWING BOLTS AND LEAKAGE WAS STOPPED. NOTIFIED SHIPPER.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT ZERWECK WAS CALLED TO TRAILER EMPU 180003 AT THE MESQUITE TOFC RAMP WHERE THE TRAILER ARRIVED LEAKING FROM THE LEFT CENTER. ZERWECK EXAMINED THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND FOUND THE LEAK AT A RATE OF 1 DROP EVERY 10 SECONDS. A PH TEST OF THE DARK VISCOUS LIQUID REVEALED 14PH. ZERWICK CALLED CHEMTREC AND WAS CONNECTED WITH KATHERINE WALLACE, DIVERSEY CORPORATION HAZMAT, WHO HIRED EMTECH TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL. EMTECH ARRIVED AT 0200 AND FOUND A 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM DUE TO ABRASION OF THE PLASTIC. THE PRODUCT WAS RESOURCE HEAVY DUTY LIQUID CAUSTIC CLEANER LABELED SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION UN1824. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AS WAS ALL CLEANING MATERIALS AND THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.
REFERRED TO DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, ONLY BOX WAS WET SO I TIGHTENED LOOSE CAPS, REBOXED, AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  I DISPOSED OF WET BOX PER DMP.
PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING IN FEEDER WHILE BEING LOADED AT BAY #52 ONE OF TWO GAL WAS CRUSHED. THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED AND SENT TO THE SHIPPER. THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: V-1 DRIVEN BY JIMMY WESTERMAN, WAS EAST BOUND ON STATE HIGHWAY 124, IN A DOWN HILL CURVE AND APPROACHING A BRIDGE. V-1 WESTERMAN'S RIGHT SIDE DROPPED OFF THE SHOULDER APPROX. 220 FT FROM THE BRIDGE AND CONTINUED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE ROAD UNTIL V-1 MADE IMPACT WITH THE BRIDGE, KNOCKING OUT APPROX. 96 FT OF BRIDGE RAILING AND CONCRETE STRUCTURE BEFORE TRAVELING OVER THE SIDE OF THE BRIDGE INTO THE CREEK. THE IMPACT WITH THE BRIDGE CAUSED AN EXPLOSION AND V-1 CAUGHT ON FIRE. THE DRIVER WESTERMAN WAS EJECTED INTO THE CREEK APPROX. 50 FT SOUTH OF THE BRIDGE. V-1 ALSO TRAVELED INTO THE CREEK JUST SOUTH OF THE BRIDGE AND CAUSED THE BRIDGE TO CATCH ON FIRE. I CANNOT DETERMINE THE FACTOR THAT CAUSED V-1 TO LEAVE THE ROADWAY. V-1 WAS TOO BADLY DAMAGED TO DETERMINE IF IT WAS A MECHANICAL PROBLEM.

column168: F.O.M., JOSEPH TORCIVIA, WAS ADVISED BY A SPOTTER THAT A TRAILER HAD FLUID LEAKING.  UPON INVESTIGATING, IT WAS FOUND THAT A DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY FREIGHT SUPERVISOR, JOSEPH FRANCZYK, AND THE DRUM IS AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

DOCKMAN, GREG CHAP, WAS UNLOADING THE SHIPMENT FROM A TRAILER AND HE NOTICED ONE SMALL PAIL (5 GALLONS) LEAKING.  HE NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR, HECTOR CAVAZOS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS SECURED AND IS BEING HELD ON THE DOCK PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON 05/30/96 OPERATIONS SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 02:47 A.M. P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN KIN HAAG WAS DISPATCHED TO "K" BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY BY SORT SUPERVISOR JEFF PENQUITE THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING GOLD PAINT WITH AN ODOR OF PAINT. UPON ARRIVAL P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN KEN HAAG FOUND THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS IN FACT LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION KEN HAAG OPENED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND A 1X1 GALLON METAL CAN OF GOLD PAINT AND A 1X1 QUART METAL CAN OF AN ACTIVATOR, BOTH OF WHICH LEAKED, BUT THE ACTUAL QUANTITY THAT LEAKED FROM EACH INNER METAL CONTAINER IS UNKNOWN. IT IS BELIEVED THAT APPROXIMATELY THREE (3) QUARTS HAD LEAKED TOTAL. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BUILDING AND PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL THE FEDERAL AVIATION COULD BE NOTIFIED. ONCE THE FEDERAL AGENCY RELEASES THE ABOVE SHIPMENT IT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE SHIPMENT WILL BE TRANSPORTED ACCORDING TO ALL APPLICABLE REGULATIONS SET FORTH BY TITLE 49CFR. SEE REPORT 96080594A
